@twildeboer Yes, this is the standard, deliberate behavior. In my opinion, even `PST` should not be processed to `tzlocal()`, but there are several places where `parse` makes the assumption that the dates you are parsing were, unless otherwise specified, generated in the locale of the program parsing them.

The reason why the other zones are not parsed is that three-letter zone names do not uniquely identify their respective zones - consider that `CST` could be China Standard Time, Cuba Standard Time or Central Standard Time, so additional context is required. For PST, the implicit context is "this probably refers to the PST that I know about" - which may or may not be valid.

The right thing to do when processing zones of this sort is to give them *explicit* context by passing a dictionary or function to the [`tzinfos`](https://dateutil.readthedocs.io/en/latest/parser.html#dateutil.parser.parse) argument mapping the 3-letter abbreviations to the appropriate `tzinfo` objects (e.g. `tzinfos={'PST': gettz('US/Pacific'), 'PDT': gettz('US/Pacific')}`).

